  section
    p.red Are the symmetric matrices $v_1v_1^T, \dots, v_nv_n^T$ linearly independent?
    p.fragment Suppose $a_1v_1v_1^T + \dots + a_nv_nv_n^T = 0$
    p.fragment $\implies v_1^T(a_1v_1v_1^T + \dots + a_nv_nv_n^T)v_1 = 0$
    p.fragment $\implies a_1 + a_2 \alpha^2 + \dots + a_n \alpha^2 = 0$
    p.fragment $\implies (1-\alpha^2)a_1 + \alpha^2(a_1 + \dots + a_n) = 0$
    p.fragment $\implies \dots \implies a_1 = \dots = a_n = 0$
  section
    h3.red The equiangular lines problem
    p In $d$ dimensions, let $N_\alpha(d)$ be the maximum number of equiangular lines with angle $\arccos\alpha$
    table
      tbody
        tr.fragment
          td 1973
          td Neumann
          td
            span $N_\alpha(d) \le 2d$
            br
            span unless $1/\alpha$ is an odd integer
        tr.fragment
          td 1973
